<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-712-637  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 712 637.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Dec 17 1990 n331 p33(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CloseUp: 1991 budgets. (communications industry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Semilof, Margie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A survey released by the International Communications Associationshows that communications budgets are shrinking.andP;  Network managersare having to cut costs by reducing equipment acquisition andhiring rather than merely controlling costs.andP;  Many communicationsmanagers are not used to a slow economy because they began theircareers in the early 1980s when the economy was stronger.andO;Managers should analyze their networks and decide if they fulfillpresent needs.andP;  Vendors may penalize customers for cutting back,but the cost of penalties should be weighed against wastefulnetworks.andP;  Outsourcing is another option for managers wishing toreduce costs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BudgetingCommunications IndustryCost ReductionNetwork ManagementInternational Communications AssociationSurveyPreview of Coming Year.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>